<i># The reason I'm a sailor 'cause #</i>

37:22.000 --> 37:28.125
<i># It's the only way to be #</i>

37:30.083 --> 37:32.000
It's a large lake, actually.

37:33.208 --> 37:35.500
I do hope the children will be safe.

37:37.125 --> 37:39.417
I do hope
the children will be safe.

37:42.333 --> 37:43.583
We should have a clear flight,

37:43.667 --> 37:45.542
provided the weather holds,
the plane flies,

37:45.625 --> 37:47.458
and none of our enemies have air cannons.

37:47.542 --> 37:50.125
- That sounds like...
- Our honeymoon.

37:51.625 --> 37:53.750
- Things worked out then.
- Well, things change.

37:53.833 --> 37:56.083
We have three children who need us,
and they need us now.

37:56.167 --> 37:59.958
- They're brave, like their mother.
- They're bold, like their father.

38:01.125 --> 38:02.792
Have you decoded the message yet?

38:03.583 --> 38:08.667
It says, "You can't lock up the barn
after the horses are gone."

38:08.750 --> 38:10.333
I hope we're not too late.

38:13.667 --> 38:16.542
- Bullet holes.
- It <i>is</i> like our honeymoon.

38:17.458 --> 38:20.875
The expression "You can't lock up the barn
after the horses are gone"

38:20.958 --> 38:23.542
was a favorite of a woman
who meant a great deal to me,

38:23.625 --> 38:26.292
even after she was trampled.

38:26.375 --> 38:29.625
The expression simply means that
sometimes even the best of plans

38:29.708 --> 38:31.625
will occur to you when it is too late,

38:31.708 --> 38:34.708
just as all of us are far, far too late

38:34.792 --> 38:37.250
to be of any help at all
to the Baudelaires.

38:38.167 --> 38:41.500
<i>I wish that I could go back somehow
and warn the Baudelaires</i>

38:41.583 --> 38:44.042
<i>about what would happen
that sorry evening.</i>

38:44.667 --> 38:48.958
I spend many sleepless nights wishing
there was some powerful invention,

38:49.042 --> 38:51.083
some crucial bit of research,

38:51.167 --> 38:54.458
<i>that might enable me to change
the Baudelaires' sad history.</i>

38:54.542 --> 38:57.583
<i>But again and again I remind myself
that there was nothing I could do,</i>

38:57.667 --> 39:00.917
<i>just as the Baudelaires could do nothing
to prevent that window from shattering.</i>

39:01.000 --> 39:02.500
What was that?

39:02.583 --> 39:03.875
It sounded like a window shattering.

39:04.542 --> 39:07.542
- Aunt Josephine!
- Aunt Josephine?

39:09.792 --> 39:11.417
Aunt Josephine...

39:37.458 --> 39:39.583
"Violet, Klaus and Sunny:

39:40.792 --> 39:43.417
By the time you read this note,
my life will be at it's end."

39:43.500 --> 39:44.500
No.

39:44.583 --> 39:48.542
"My heart is as cold as Ike,
and I find my life inbearable."

39:48.625 --> 39:50.375
Aunt Josephine.

39:52.250 --> 39:55.000
It is impossible to go back, of course,

39:55.083 --> 39:58.625
and tell the Baudelaires that their fears
that night were entirely rational.

39:58.708 --> 40:01.708
It is impossible to go back
and tell them anything at all,

40:01.792 --> 40:04.417
just as it is impossible
to put Aunt Josephine's house

40:04.500 --> 40:06.167
back on top of this cliff.

40:08.417 --> 40:10.000
I can tell you something.

40:10.083 --> 40:12.667
I can tell you that,
as the Baudelaires stood there

40:12.750 --> 40:15.792
and gazed out the wide window
of Josephine's house,

40:15.875 --> 40:18.958
- believing that their guardian was dead...
- Aunt Josephine.

40:19.042 --> 40:20.375
that they were wrong.

40:21.500 --> 40:24.833
I can tell you that
Aunt Josephine was not dead at all.

